## 3. Positioning of the contribution (469v; 9KyP)

Two reviewers found it difficult to identify what is new, from opposite
directions: one asked which examples genuinely require our algorithm, the other
noted that covariate-dependent priors are standard in hierarchical Bayes. Both
are right, and the two concerns have a common resolution.

Our contribution is **not** the covariate-dependent prior --- that is a familiar
modelling device --- and **not** a general-purpose speedup for empirical Bayes
regression. It is that split VEB makes an *arbitrary neural parameterisation* of
the prior computable at scale, in a regime where direct CAVI requires
$\mathcal{O}(p)$ network backward passes per sweep and MCMC is infeasible. For
closed-form prior families (ash, group-linear), standard CAVI is already
efficient and our method offers no advantage; we have said so explicitly and
added a table classifying each example accordingly.

\rev{Sections 1, 2 and 4 have been revised to make this scope explicit.}

## 4. A clarification on the design assumption

Our presentation invited a misreading, and we want to correct it plainly: **Nash
does not require a fixed design, and our simulations do not use one.** In every
scenario of Appendix B.1 and B.2 the matrix $X$ is drawn independently in each
replicate, so all reported errors are averaged over the design distribution
rather than conditional on a single realisation. The derivation conditions on $X$
in the usual sense for penalised and empirical Bayes regression, but assumes
nothing about it being non-random.

The ambiguity came from Table 3, whose "Fixed parameters" column refers to
simulation settings held constant and not to a fixed design matrix.
\rev{We have relabelled that column and stated the per-replicate redraw
explicitly in Appendix B.1.}

Separately --- and this is a real limitation rather than a misreading --- our
designs are Gaussian, and our noise is homoscedastic and independent in all
scenarios (Eq. 55). \rev{We have added non-Gaussian designs ($t_3$ rows;
discrete genotype-like columns) and non-standard residual structures
(heteroscedastic; AR(1) correlated), and the Limitations section now states the
homoscedasticity assumption, which it previously did not.}
